				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$r_f$$\end{document}) (Fig. 4A and Fig. 4B). Fifty-three significant phenotypic correlations were identified, with coefficients ranging from -0.64 to 0.96. Among these, 35 were significant at 0.1%, 7 at 1%, 12 at 5%, and 24 were not significant (Fig. 4A). Among genetic correlations, 55 were significant, with coefficients ranging from -0.64 to 0.96, including 37 at 0.1%, 5 at 1%, 14 at 5%, and 22 not significant (Fig. 4B).Fig. 4
