With the removal of traits exhibiting VIF values greater than five, the path analysis yielded an \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$R^2$$\end{document} estimate exceeding 0.70 and an EVR of 0.4408, indicating a good model fit for explaining variations in IQD. The presence of at least one trait with a VIF greater than five is sufficient for the associated regression coefficients to be highly influenced by multicollinearity44, highlighting the importance of excluding such traits from the analysis. In cases of high correlation but low direct effect, the most effective strategy for achieving satisfactory improvements in the primary variable is the simultaneous selection of traits, with emphasis on those exhibiting significant indirect effects43.

Emergence and morphometric traits of fruits and seeds exhibited high \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
