				\begin{document}$$H^2$$\end{document} estimates. The significant positive \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$r_g$$\end{document} between the morphometric characteristics of fruits and seeds and those related to growth indicates the potential for using these descriptors for early indirect selection to develop higher-quality seedlings. For seedling selection targeting quality (DQI), indirect selection can be primarily based on LA and DBS. Path analysis confirmed that LA and DSB exert the strongest direct effects on DQI, reinforcing their role as reliable early indicators of seedling quality. The detection of significant genetic variability for all traits, especially fruit and seed biometric characteristics, highlights the existence of broad genetic diversity among the E. edulis genotypes evaluated. Moreover, the low significance of genotype \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
